Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 475 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Core, deseed, and dice @long green pepper{1%unit}(cored, deseeded, and diced). Finely dice @tomato{1%unit}(finely diced). Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2%units}(trimmed and thinly sliced), separating whites from greens. Thinly slice @chili pepper{1%unit}(thinly sliced).

Drain @black beans{1%unit}(drained, liquid reserved) over a #small bowl{}, reserving liquid.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tablespoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add green pepper and cook until just softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add @ground plant-based protein{6%ounce} to pan; using a #spatula{}, press into an even layer. Cook, undisturbed, until browned on bottom, ~{3-4%minutes}. Break up protein into pieces and continue cooking until browned all over and warmed through, ~{3-4%minutes} more.

Reserve ½ tsp @Southwest spice blend{1%tablespoon} (1 tsp for 4 servings) in a second small bowl for step 6.

To pan with filling, add tomato, scallion whites, half the beans, remaining Southwest Spice Blend, and 2 TBSP reserved bean liquid (you'll use the remaining beans and more bean liquid in the next step). Cook, stirring, until fragrant and warmed through, ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a large drizzle of oil in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add remaining beans and cook, stirring, until slightly softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add 3 TBSP reserved bean liquid (1⁄3 cup for 4 servings). (You may have some bean liquid left over.) Simmer until warmed through, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Reduce heat to low and stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4). Season with salt and pepper.

Turn off heat; mash with a #potato masher{} or #fork{} until mostly smooth. Season generously with salt and pepper.

Spread @flour tortillas{6%units} with mashed beans. Place a small amount of filling on one half of each tortilla. Roll up tortillas, starting with filled sides, and place, seam sides down, in an #8-by-11-inch baking dish{} or #ovenproof pan{}.

(For 4 servings, use a 9-by-13-inch baking dish or two smaller ones.)

Top with enough @green salsa{7.06%ounce} to generously coat (you may have some left over). Sprinkle with @Monterey Jack cheese{1/4%cup}.

Bake on top rack until salsa is bubbly and cheese melts, ~{3-5%minutes}.

While enchiladas bake, add @sour cream{1.5%tablespoon} to #bowl{} with reserved Southwest Spice Blend. Stir in warm water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Season with salt and pepper.

Top baked enchiladas with crema, scallion greens, and as much chili as you like. Divide between plates and serve.

> Ground Plant-Based Protein is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.